PartOrg: Dolphin Research Center (DRC)and FWC Volunteer Kit Curtain under direction of FWC SEFL.
Comments: DRC used cutting pole to remove monofilament which was deeply embedded around both flippers and formed a 2-inch-wide mass of line that “handcuffed” the manatee.  The entanglements were associated with swollen, white scar tissue at the proximal third of both flippers. All gear was removed. FWC volunteer Kit Curtain also responded and verified manatee was gear-free. Dually was reported with a second year calf.
The monofilament that was over the dorsum was cut but line remained wrapped around each flipper. An estimated 8 inches of monofilament was still trailing from each flipper.

PartOrg: At 742 hrs,FWC-JDC received a text from FWC SO Dispatch-Miami regarding an entangled manatee in Miami,Miami-Dade County, in Biscayne Bay. FWC case number 0569 was assigned. Miami Seaquarium’s Jodie Tuzinski along with Miami Police Department responded to the scene. The manatee had a rope, that was attached to the dock,entangled around its flipper. Jodie informed JDC that she believed if the rope was cut near the flipper the entire entanglement would come off the animal.
Comments: After discussing the situation,JDC authorized Jodie to attempt to remove the rope. Using Miami Police Department’s boat, Jodie was able to get close enough to the manatee to cut the rope from its flipper. The line became loose and the manatee was able to swim away,suffering only from abrasions around the flipper.

Manatee last seen swimming irratically in the shallows when officers went to collect rescue staff.  Manatee could not be relocated.

PartOrg: FWC received a call from the Canaveral Locks regarding a manatee trapped on the inside door of lock gate #3 (NE side). Army Core's, Sharon Tyson and FWC's Christine Rush responded to the scene. BCSO dive team was sent to assess how the manatee got into the gate. After inspecting the gate, there was a large hole that ran from 8 to 16 feet down the gate.
Comments: The dive team attempted to spook the manatee towards the hole to get out but that was unsuccessful.  Another hole was created, much more shallow, where the manatee preferred to rest. A hose was run from the outside of the hole, in, so the manatee would detect the it.  The manatee eventually swam out around 1400 hrs.

 On 22 June 2020, the manatee was released.

On 11 June 2020, FWC received an email regarding an incidental catch of a manatee in Sarasota. On 08 June 2020, FWC FIM set a seine along a shoreline in Robert's Bay. Immediately after completing the set, the manatee struck the opposite side of the net. The crew members began retrieving the net to allow the animal to escape. SFWMD continued to monitor the area to ensure there were no other entrapped manatees.

FWC SWFL received a report of a lethargic manatee in Smokehouse Bay, Marco Island. SWFL requested assistance from an FWC volunteer, who kayaked to the manatee’s location at 1011 hrs and confirmed it was unreactive and disoriented (e.g., rolling over and sinking). The volunteer was instructed to elicit breaths by lifting its head with the kayak paddle while SWFL were en route. After 30 min, the manatee was more reactive and swimming away, so the decision was made to cancel this response.

PartOrg: FWC SWFL, FWC LE, Rookery Bay National Estuarine and Research Reserve
Comments: SWFL-DMB received a picture from a manatee tour guide regarding an entangled manatee in Faka Union Canal, near Port of the Islands. FWC LE arrived and were informed that a citizen had cut the line between the manatee and the entangling trap, and it was now free swimming with buoy and line attached.  For two hours, FWC SWFL and RBBNEER staff attempted to disentangle the manatee via kayak and vessel but were unsuccessful due to the animal’s evasiveness. No further verified reports were received.

Comments: SWFL staff responded to an entangled adult manatee in the Myakka River. The manatee was reported the following day, and SWFL was able to get images of the entanglement. From the assessment, it was determined the left flipper was wrapped with line and the manatee was dragging a trap. A VHF tag was clipped to the entanglement. The next day, a team resighted the manatee. The manatee was captured and it was determined the damage from the entanglement was not severe, so the manatee was released.

PartOrg: FWC Indian River Lab FIM staff
Comments: At 0901 hrs, FWC biologists- Z Frame, C French, D Tremain, and M Sandberg accidentally caught a manatee while tripping the bag of a seine net. The crew immediately pushed down the floats and the manatee was able to swim out of the net. No injuries were observed before or after capture. No photos were available.

At 1015 hrs, FWC FIM set a haul seine and halfway through the pull, realized a manatee was in the net. The manatee swam around the sample area seemingly undisturbed. The crew turned the boat motor off carefully pulled one side of the net out to create a small opening for the animal to swim out. The manatee swam out and did not appeared disturbed during the process. No clear photos of the manatee were taken. The information was passed to the Southwest Field Station on 7/22/2021.

Comments: On July 22nd, FWC SWFL received a report of a manatee in Longboat Key, Sarasota County. The citizen reported a manatee that was struggling to breathe and appeared disoriented. MML personnel arrived to support the manatee’s head until SWFL staff arrived. SWFL arrived at 1215 hrs. As the boat approached the manatee, it became more responsive and swam out of the hands of MML staff. The manatee was now more reactive and evasive. For this reason, the decision was made to cancel this response.

Mote Marine Lab received a report of a mating herd in Sarasota, Sarasota County. After RSW2122, SWFL arrived at the mating herd location to monitor for harassment and conduct Photo ID. Upon arrival, three manatees that were grounded in shallow water had become beached due to an outgoing tide. After receiving approval from USFWS, the decision was made to assist and release due to the concern of overheating. The manatee was released at 1700 hrs and swam into deeper water at 1743 hrs.

Comments: At 1211 hrs, VLZ received a direct report regarding a beached manatee at the waterline in the Gulf of Mexico, Fort Myers Beach, Lee County. LCSO arrived on scene at 1248 hrs. AMS, AMK and H. Drymon arrived on scene at 1408 hrs. The manatee was stretchered and loaded into SWFL transport truck at 1415 hrs. The animal was transported to Orange Harbor Boat Ramp and was transferred into the ZooTampa transport truck at 1520 hrs. The manatee died naturally in the transport truck at 1550 hrs.
Citizen disentanglement. Entanglement on left pectoral flipper, line and buoy were recovered and citizens verified manatee was gear free.

PrimText: Entrapped in man-made pond accessed during flooding due to Tropical Storm Debby.
PartOrg: FWC MMPL, US Fish and Wildlife Service, Clearwater Marine Aquarium, University of Florida.
Comments: Entrapped in a man-made pond on the Plantation Inn Golf Course. The manatee gained access during flooding from Hurricane Debby and was unable to exit once storm waters receded. The manatee was captured and released into a different pond with open access to Kings Bay.

PartOrg: FWC MMPL, FWC FWRI, ZooTampa, Clearwater Marine Aquarium, University of Florida
Comments: The manatee accessed the retention pond system during higher-than-normal tides due to Hurricane Debby. When water levels receded the manatee became entrapped. The manatee was captured and transported to nearby Veterans Memorial Park where it was released into Safety Harbor.

Deputies from Pinellas County Sherriff's Office responded to an entangled manatee. Prior to speaking to FWC biologists, the Deputies cut the line from the manatee and placed the gear (float, line and trap) was placed on the seawall.

PartOrg: FWC SEFL, FWC LE, USCG, Citizen
Comments: Tidally stranded on a sandbar, in good body condition and good energy for relocation and release into deeper water

PartOrg: FWC-SWFL (Denise Boyd, Abigail Steele, Victoria Zelinski). Lee County Sheriff's Office (Deputies Tony Smith, Joseph Laird).
Comments: Entanglement consisted of one wrap of thin-diameter line around the right pectoral flipper near the axilla and was associated with a white buoy and recreational blue crab trap. The entanglement was not embedded and the manatee was in good condition. A telemetry tag was applied, and a remote in-water disentanglement was conducted. The animal's flipper slipped out of the wrapped line and self-disentangled when tension was placed on either aspect of the gear. All gear removed cleanly.
Incidental capture during rescue of REC2401.
Manatee was rescued from culvert structure but into a mosquito impoundment.

PrimText: Stranded in a small puddle on MacDill Air Force Base following Hurricane Helene.
WhereRel: MacDill Air Force Base boat ramp
PartOrg: Clearwater Marine Aquarium, US Fish and Wildlife Service, US Air Force personnel
Comments: A portion of the perimeter fence at MacDill Air Force Base was knocked down during Hurrican Helene. Flood waters from the storm surge allowed the manatee to access a low-lying area near the runway. When waters receded the manatee became stranded. A rescue team responded and relocated the manatee to the boat ramp on base for release.

PartOrg: The manatee was entrapped in a landlocked canal system. The manatee likely gained access to the system with the storm surge from Hurricane Helene.
Comments: The manatee was entrapped in a landlocked canal system. The manatee likely gained access to the system with the storm surge from Hurricane Helene. The manatee was captured and relocated to the Hernando Beach Public Boat Ramp for release.

PrimText: Animal was found 1.5 miles inland after storm surge from Hurricane Helene
SecText: Animal presented as thin.

Comments: Entrapped in canal system.   Gained access to system from hurricane through a culvert system.  Animal had superficial wounds on face.

PartOrg: Mote Marine Lab, Lee County Sheriff's Office, ZooTampa
Comments: On 04 November, FWC received an alert regarding an injured manatee in St. James City, Lee County. A rescue team arrived at 1315 hrs and the manatee was caught by hoop net on the fourth attempt. The manatee was loaded into the Southwest Transport truck and died naturally at 1354 hrs while en route to ZooTampa for rehabilitation. The carcass was transported to the Southwest Field Lab. 05 November, a field necropsy was completed.

Manatee gained access to the impoundment through an ungrated culvert on Merritt Island National Wildlife Refuge.  Primary cause of rescue should be entrapment, then natural orphan calf as secondary cause.
